The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to overexploitation and war, and in which the growing production capacity of the last decades leads to more pollution and global warming.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, still influences the environmental movement today.
On the other hand, the optimists claim that everything will get better – human health, the standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
Their opponents see them as "economists of abundance," who trust the market, supposedly solving all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see whether the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing an evaluation list of the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender relations, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists have all answered the same question: How high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts up to 2050.
Based on classical economic assessments of all factors from death tolls, health damages, and illiteracy through the destruction of wetlands to higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists outline the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the scale of the problem, it is compared with the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let us consider gender inequality.
In essence, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the world's workforce was female.
What are the losses that resulted from this small proportion?
Even when we take into account the higher costs of educating women and the fact that someone has to perform unpaid household work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor participation rate and smaller income disparities, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring mostly increasing net benefits – rising up to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the costs.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
A moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, equivalent to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, with further rising temperatures, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs, justifying cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the evaluation list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, putting things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating, which corresponds to a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will decline to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators around the world have improved the most.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had changed little.
The magnitude of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overstated: At that time, global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it stands at 69 years (and is likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The greatest factor was the decline in child mortality.
In 1970, for example, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, this had risen to 85%, which has led to the saving of three million lives every year—more than would have been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised an additional 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to astonishing 32% of global GDP.
Today they have decreased to about 11% and are expected to be halved again by 2050.
Even if the optimists are not right in all respects (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and significantly more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no problems left.
Even though they have become smaller in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should gradually get used to the idea that the world has improved significantly.
In addition, the evaluation list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not base our view of the future on the scariest stories or the loudest interest groups, but on objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
